{"cursor":"26519","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Free content', or 'free information', is any kind of functional work, artwork,\nor other creative content that meets the definition of a free cultural\nwork. http://freecontentdefinition.org/Definition A free cultural work\nis one which has no significant legal restriction on people's freedom: *to use\nthe content and benefit from using it, *to study the content and apply what is\nlearned, *to make and distribute copies of the content, *to change and improve\nthe content and distribute these derivative works.\n\nAlthough different definitions are used, free content is legally similar if not\nidentical to open content. An analogy is the use of the rival terms free\nsoftware and open source which describe ideological differences rather than\nlegal ones.\n\nFree content encompasses all works in the public domain and also those\ncopyrighted works whose licenses honor and uphold the freedoms mentioned above.\nBecause copyright law in most countries by default grants copyright holders\nmonopolistic control over their creations, copyright content must be explicitly\ndeclared free, usually by the referencing or inclusion of licensing statements\nfrom within the work.\n\nThough a work which is in the public domain because its copyright has expired is\nconsidered free, it can become non-free again if the copyright law\nchanges.\n","linknr":526,"url":"Free_content","recorded":1362535054,"links":86,"instances":["publishing"],"pdf":["http://www.valt.helsinki.fi/staff/herkia/kava/Seminnarit/MI_mustonen.pdf","http://www.valt.helsinki.fi/staff/herkia/kava/Seminnarit/MI_mustonen.pdf","http://hal.inria.fr/docs/00/28/33/44/PDF/RR-6519.pdf","http://hal.inria.fr/docs/00/28/33/44/PDF/RR-6519.pdf","http://www.isb.vt.edu/news/2005/artspdf/dec0501.pdf","http://www.isb.vt.edu/news/2005/artspdf/dec0501.pdf","http://eprints.ecs.soton.ac.uk/10999/1/jisc2.pdf","http://eprints.ecs.soton.ac.uk/10999/1/jisc2.pdf","http://ww